     4→[<img alt="github" src="https://img.shields.io/badge/github-dtolnay/thiserror-8da0cb?style=for-the-badge&labelColor=555555&logo=github" height="20">](https://github.com/dtolnay/thiserror)
     5→[<img alt="crates.io" src="https://img.shields.io/crates/v/thiserror.svg?style=for-the-badge&color=fc8d62&logo=rust" height="20">](https://crates.io/crates/thiserror)
     6→[<img alt="docs.rs" src="https://img.shields.io/badge/docs.rs-thiserror-66c2a5?style=for-the-badge&labelColor=555555&logo=docs.rs" height="20">](https://docs.rs/thiserror)
     7→[<img alt="build status" src="https://img.shields.io/github/actions/workflow/status/dtolnay/thiserror/ci.yml?branch=master&style=for-the-badge" height="20">](https://github.com/dtolnay/thiserror/actions?query=branch%3Amaster)
     8→
     9→This library provides a convenient derive macro for the standard library's
    10→[`std::error::Error`] trait.
    11→
    12→[`std::error::Error`]: https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/error/trait.Error.html
    13→
    14→```toml
    15→[dependencies]
    16→thiserror = "2"
    17→```
    18→
    19→<br>
    20→
    21→## Example
    23→```rust
    24→use thiserror::Error;
    25→
    26→#[derive(Error, Debug)]
    27→pub enum DataStoreError {
    28→    #[error("data store disconnected")]
    29→    Disconnect(#[from] io::Error),
    30→    #[error("the data for key `{0}` is not available")]
    31→    Redaction(String),
    32→    #[error("invalid header (expected {expected:?}, found {found:?})")]
    33→    InvalidHeader {
    34→        expected: String,
    35→        found: String,
    36→    },
    37→    #[error("unknown data store error")]
    38→    Unknown,
    39→}
    40→```
    41→
    42→<br>
    43→
    44→## Details
    46→- Thiserror deliberately does not appear in your public API. You get the same
    47→  thing as if you had written an implementation of `std::error::Error` by hand,
    48→  and switching from handwritten impls to thiserror or vice versa is not a
    49→  breaking change.
    50→
    51→- Errors may be enums, structs with named fields, tuple structs, or unit
    52→  structs.
    53→
    54→- A `Display` impl is generated for your error if you provide `#[error("...")]`
    55→  messages on the struct or each variant of your enum, as shown above in the
    56→  example.
    57→
    58→  The messages support a shorthand for interpolating fields from the error.
    59→
    60→    - `#[error("{var}")]`&ensp;⟶&ensp;`write!("{}", self.var)`
    61→    - `#[error("{0}")]`&ensp;⟶&ensp;`write!("{}", self.0)`
    62→    - `#[error("{var:?}")]`&ensp;⟶&ensp;`write!("{:?}", self.var)`
    63→    - `#[error("{0:?}")]`&ensp;⟶&ensp;`write!("{:?}", self.0)`
    64→
    65→  These shorthands can be used together with any additional format args, which
    66→  may be arbitrary expressions. For example:
    67→
    68→  ```rust
    69→  #[derive(Error, Debug)]
    70→  pub enum Error {
    71→      #[error("invalid rdo_lookahead_frames {0} (expected < {max})", max = i32::MAX)]
    72→      InvalidLookahead(u32),
    73→  }
    74→  ```
    75→
    76→  If one of the additional expression arguments needs to refer to a field of the
    77→  struct or enum, then refer to named fields as `.var` and tuple fields as `.0`.
    78→
    79→  ```rust
    80→  #[derive(Error, Debug)]
    81→  pub enum Error {
    82→      #[error("first letter must be lowercase but was {:?}", first_char(.0))]
    83→      WrongCase(String),
    84→      #[error("invalid index {idx}, expected at least {} and at most {}", .limits.lo, .limits.hi)]
    85→      OutOfBounds { idx: usize, limits: Limits },
    86→  }
    87→  ```
    88→
    89→- A `From` impl is generated for each variant that contains a `#[from]`
    90→  attribute.
    91→
    92→  The variant using `#[from]` must not contain any other fields beyond the
    93→  source error (and possibly a backtrace &mdash; see below). Usually `#[from]`
    94→  fields are unnamed, but `#[from]` is allowed on a named field too.
    95→
    96→  ```rust
    97→  #[derive(Error, Debug)]
    98→  pub enum MyError {
    99→      Io(#[from] io::Error),
   100→      Glob(#[from] globset::Error),
   101→  }
   102→  ```
   103→
   104→- The Error trait's `source()` method is implemented to return whichever field
   105→  has a `#[source]` attribute or is named `source`, if any. This is for
   106→  identifying the underlying lower level error that caused your error.
   107→
   108→  The `#[from]` attribute always implies that the same field is `#[source]`, so
   109→  you don't ever need to specify both attributes.
   110→
   111→  Any error type that implements `std::error::Error` or dereferences to `dyn
   112→  std::error::Error` will work as a source.
   113→
   114→  ```rust
   115→  #[derive(Error, Debug)]
   116→  pub struct MyError {
   117→      msg: String,
   118→      #[source]  // optional if field name is `source`
   119→      source: anyhow::Error,
   120→  }
   121→  ```
   122→
   123→- The Error trait's `provide()` method is implemented to provide whichever field
   124→  has a type named `Backtrace`, if any, as a `std::backtrace::Backtrace`. Using
   125→  `Backtrace` in errors requires a nightly compiler with Rust version 1.73 or
   126→  newer.
   127→
   128→  ```rust
   129→  use std::backtrace::Backtrace;
   130→
   131→  #[derive(Error, Debug)]
   132→  pub struct MyError {
   133→      msg: String,
   134→      backtrace: Backtrace,  // automatically detected
   135→  }
   136→  ```
   137→
   138→- If a field is both a source (named `source`, or has `#[source]` or `#[from]`
   139→  attribute) *and* is marked `#[backtrace]`, then the Error trait's `provide()`
   140→  method is forwarded to the source's `provide` so that both layers of the error
   141→  share the same backtrace. The `#[backtrace]` attribute requires a nightly
   142→  compiler with Rust version 1.73 or newer.
   143→
   144→
   145→  ```rust
   146→  #[derive(Error, Debug)]
   147→  pub enum MyError {
   148→      Io {
   149→          #[backtrace]
   150→          source: io::Error,
   151→      },
   152→  }
   153→  ```
   154→
   155→- For variants that use `#[from]` and also contain a `Backtrace` field, a
   156→  backtrace is captured from within the `From` impl.
   157→
   158→  ```rust
   159→  #[derive(Error, Debug)]
   160→  pub enum MyError {
   161→      Io {
   162→          #[from]
   163→          source: io::Error,
   164→          backtrace: Backtrace,
   165→      },
   166→  }
   167→  ```
   168→
   169→- Errors may use `error(transparent)` to forward the source and Display methods
   170→  straight through to an underlying error without adding an additional message.
   171→  This would be appropriate for enums that need an "anything else" variant.
   172→
   173→  ```rust
   174→  #[derive(Error, Debug)]
   175→  pub enum MyError {
   176→      ...
   177→
   178→      #[error(transparent)]
   179→      Other(#[from] anyhow::Error),  // source and Display delegate to anyhow::Error
   180→  }
   181→  ```
   182→
   183→  Another use case is hiding implementation details of an error representation
   184→  behind an opaque error type, so that the representation is able to evolve
   185→  without breaking the crate's public API.
   186→
   187→  ```rust
   188→  // PublicError is public, but opaque and easy to keep compatible.
   189→  #[derive(Error, Debug)]
   190→  #[error(transparent)]
   191→  pub struct PublicError(#[from] ErrorRepr);
   192→
   193→  impl PublicError {
   194→      // Accessors for anything we do want to expose publicly.
   195→  }
   196→
   197→  // Private and free to change across minor version of the crate.
   198→  #[derive(Error, Debug)]
   199→  enum ErrorRepr {
   200→      ...
   201→  }
   202→  ```
   203→
   204→- See also the [`anyhow`] library for a convenient single error type to use in
   205→  application code.
   206→
   207→  [`anyhow`]: https://github.com/dtolnay/anyhow
   208→
   209→<br>
   210→
   211→## Comparison to anyhow
   213→Use thiserror if you care about designing your own dedicated error type(s) so
   214→that the caller receives exactly the information that you choose in the event of
   215→failure. This most often applies to library-like code. Use [Anyhow] if you don't
   216→care what error type your functions return, you just want it to be easy. This is
   217→common in application-like code.
   218→
   219→[Anyhow]: https://github.com/dtolnay/anyhow
   220→
